<subSubSection lastPageId="43" lastPageNumber="44" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="43" lastPageNumber="44" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
Only one species is known. Unfortunately, the location for the type material is unknown. The original description of 
<taxonomicName authority="Harold, 1875" authorityName="Harold" authorityYear="1875" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Pydaristes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pydaristes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pydaristes</taxonomicName>
appears to be identical or 
<pageBreakToken pageId="43" pageNumber="44" start="start">very</pageBreakToken>
close to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Chapuis, 1875" authorityName="Chapuis" authorityYear="1875" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Amphimela" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amphimela" order="Coleoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Amphimela</taxonomicName>
Chapuis. The synonymy proposed by 
<bibRefCitation pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Scherer (1961)</bibRefCitation>
between 
<taxonomicName authority="Harold, 1875" authorityName="Harold" authorityYear="1875" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Pydaristes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pydaristes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pydaristes</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Blepharida" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Blepharida" order="Coleoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Blepharida</taxonomicName>
Chevrolat is unconvincing, because of the absence of dentiform emargination on the hind tibiae in 
<taxonomicName authority="Harold, 1875" authorityName="Harold" authorityYear="1875" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Pydaristes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pydaristes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pydaristes</taxonomicName>
(according to the original description), such emargination is characteristically present in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Blepharida" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Blepharida" order="Coleoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Blepharida</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
